column1: #Text=( I shall stop here and go down to the pantry .
#Text=I could eat no dinner , being filled with emotion .
#Text=But I must keep strong if I am to help Adrian in his trouble .
#Text=The mince pie was excellent , but after all pastry does not take the place of solid food . )
#Text=LATER :
#Text=I shall now go on with my recital .
#Text=As the theater was almost empty , at the end of Act One I put on the pink hat and left it on as though absent-minded .
#Text=There was no one behind me .
#Text=And , although during act one I had thought that he perhaps felt my presence , he had not once looked directly at me .
#Text=But the hat captured his errant gaze , as one may say .
#Text=And , after capture , it remained on my face , so much so that I flushed and a woman sitting near with a very plain girl in a skunk collar , observed :
#Text=" Really , it is outrageous . "
#Text=Now came a moment which I thrill even to recollect .
#Text=For Adrian plucked a pink rose from a vase -- he was in the millionaire 's house , and was starving in the midst of luxury -- and held it to his lips .
#Text=The rose , not the house , of course .
#Text=Looking over it , he smiled down at me .
#Text=LATER :
#Text=It is midnight .
#Text=I cannot sleep .
#Text=Perchance he too , is lying awake .
#Text=I am sitting at the window in my robe de nuit .
#Text=Below , mother and Sis have just come in , and Smith has slammed the door of the car and gone back to the garage .
#Text=How puny is the life my family leads !
#Text=Nothing but eating and playing , with no higher thoughts .
#Text=A man has just gone by .
#Text=For a moment I thought I recognized the footstep .
#Text=But no , it was but the night watchman .
#Text=JANUARY 17TH .
#Text=Father still away .
#Text=No money , as mother absolutely refuses on account of Maddie Mackenzie 's gown , which she had to send away to be repaired .
#Text=JANUARY 18TH .
#Text=Father still away .
#Text=The Hon. sent Sis a huge bunch of orchids today .
#Text=She refused me even one .
#Text=She is always tight with flowers and candy .
#Text=JANUARY 19TH .
#Text=The paper says that Adrian 's play is going to close the end of next week .
#Text=No business .
#Text=How can I endure to know that he is suffering , and that I cannot help , even to the extent of buying one ticket ?
#Text=Matinee today , and no money .
#Text=Father still away .
#Text=I have tried to do a kind deed today , feeling that perhaps it would soften mother 's heart and she would advance my allowance .
#Text=I offered to manicure her nails for her , but she refused , saying that as Hannah had done it for many years , she guessed she could manage now .
#Text=JANUARY 20TH .
#Text=Today I did a desperate thing , dear Diary .
#Text="
#Text=The Sermon gave me courage to go on .
#Text=When he said , " Women today step in where men are afraid to tread , and bring success out of failure , " I felt that it was meant for me .
#Text=Had no money for the plate , and mother attempted to smuggle a half dollar to me .
#Text=I refused , however , as if I cannot give my own money to the heathen , I will give none .
#Text=Mother turned pale , and the man with the plate gave me a black look .
#Text=What can he know of my reasons ?
#Text=Beresford lunched with us , and as I discouraged him entirely , he was very attentive to Sis .
#Text=Mother is planing a big wedding , and I found Sis in the store room yesterday looking up mother 's wedding veil .
#Text=No old stuff for me .
#Text=I guess Beresford is trying to forget that he kissed my hand the other night , for he called me " Little Miss Barbara " today , meaning little in the sense of young .
#Text=I gave him a stern glance .
#Text=" I am not any littler than the other night , " I observed .
#Text=" That was merely an affectionate diminutive , " he said , looking uncomfortable .
#Text=" If you do n't mind , " I said coldly , " you might do as you have heretofore -- reserve your affectionate advances until we are alone . "
#Text=" Barbara ! " mother said .
#Text=And began quickly to talk about a Lady Something or other we 'd met on a train in Switzerland .
#Text=Because --

#Text=they can talk until they are black in the face , dear Diary , but it is true we do not know any of the British Nobility , except the aforementioned and the man who comes once a year with flavoring extracts , who says he is the third son of a baronet .
#Text=Every one being out this afternoon , I suddenly had an inspiration , and sent for Carter Brooks .

#Text=I then put my hair up and put on my blue silk , because while I do not believe in woman using her feminine charm when talking business , I do believe that she should look her best under any and all circumstances .
#Text=He was rather surprised not to find Sis in , as I had used her name in telephoning .
#Text=" I did it , " I explained , " because I knew that you felt no interest in me , and I had to see you . "
